metadata.name: Apophenia #49
metadata.description:
Apophenia is the art of seeing things in patterns that aren't 'really' there.
Frogs and tadpoles, small waving aliens, turtles, seahorses and bits of elephant - our brains will search for something we recognise in the randomness and chaos.
This pattern is made by tessellating hexagons. There are 12 unique hexagon possibilities plus reflections and rotations which bring the total possible for each placement in the design to 46.
Features include a choice of 7 colour palettes, 11 scales and the drawing of a grid behind the main pattern or not. Most rare are the very large or small scale with grid lines in a colour that isn't Teal and Peach.

metadata.name: Vlinder #20
metadata.description:
An homage to the incredible diversity of nature. I did a precursor to these butterflies (vlinder, in Dutch) all the way back in 2016. Google 'butterfly effect shadertoy' to see it.

The entire thing is procedurally generated in a shader that has about 500 lines of code. 

There is A LOT of variety in them: wing shape, pattern, body shape, antennae, colors, as well as some very rare traits that will only come out with a large enough number of editions. A bunch of them can look kind of bland, but every once in a while you get a real beauty! To save an image, just right-click -> 'save as image'

I hope that down the line it will be possible to 'mate' two vlinders and then generate new 'offspring' vlinders that are a mix of their parents. Someone made a shadertoy that does exactly that with my original 2016 effect and its super cool. So, fxhash, if you are reading this... ;)

metadata.name: Action Fields #198
metadata.description:
A generative painting based on abstract expressionism and the action paintings of Jackson Pollock.

Several different flow fields are used to create paths which are then painted in one of four different styles (pastel, paint, Pollock, black+gold). Additional features affect the background, path length + angles, level of detail, and mess (drips and splats). 

NOTES: 
- Some variations of the Pollock style may appear slightly different between browsers, but will render consistently in the same browser. 
- On slower devices, it may take some time to being drawing due to the background rendering.
- If you get a browser warning that the page is taking a long time, press continue.

Viewing in desktop Chrome is recommended for the best results.
Press â€™sâ€™ to save a screenshot. Image size is 1200x928px
Press â€™pâ€™ to pause/resume.

Add '&size=#' to the end of the live view URL to render a variation of your edition at a resolution from 300 to 5,000 px. The ideal higher resolution is 2,000px.

metadata.name: Organicon, variation II #125
metadata.description:
Generative art by Frederik Vanhoutte, @wblut
One of 128 unique generators creating an endless sequence of iterations with fixed features

Organicon, variation II is a slow piece, meant to build on the screen. A small counter in the lower-right corner displays the progress.

Interface: on first load the piece operates in active mode. In this mode an iteration is cleared 30s after completion and replaced by the next iteration. This mode is indicated by a flashing dot in the upper-right corner.

A first mouse click disables active mode. The current iteration will complete and remain on screen. A second mouse click clears the screen, loads the next iteration, and reenables active mode.

metadata.name: Balanced #212
metadata.description:
What does balance look like when viewed through the lens of pure mathematics? This is the question Balanced attempts to answer.

Each output is composed of a unique collection of blocks mathematically stacked to be in perfect balance.

This is my Genesis project. Enjoy!

Interactions:
1 - Reverse your stack vertically and re-balance.
2 - Toggle between square and portrait frame.
3 - Show center of mass. 
4 - Toggle the border.
5 - Toggle the background (color/transparent)
6 - Export image (2048x2048)
7 - Export image (4096x4096)
8 - Export image (8192x8192)

How it was made: https://www.jeffweber.art/balanced

metadata.name: Ridge Scribbles #209
metadata.description:
Ridge scribbles is the first piece of a small series around mountain landscapes using different rendering techniques.

A heightmap is generated using fractal noise with different parameters and scales. Then we generate tens of thousands of paths by using a gradient descent algorithm with momentum, starting at random positions on the reversed heightmap. Those paths are then rendered using one of 11 different colour palettes.

Press "s" to save a screenshot.

Original artwork by William Watkins Â· Lyon, 2022

metadata.name: Sketchbook Splash #25
metadata.description:
A splash of color on some scribbled shapes.

There are several keybindings to modify the image:
'1' - Toggles watercolors
'2' - Toggles overlaying constrast shapes 
'3' - Toggles sketch outlines
'4' - Toggles shape/splatter clipping (will fill the entire canvas with watercolor!)
'B' - Cycles borders; black, white, all colors in the palette being used, and no border

Play around to find something you like, and then press 'S' to download a copy of your image. 
You can also modify the URL parameters at the end of the URL to change the size of the image, such as &x=2560&y=1440. Keep in mind that this will result in a slightly different image, but colors/shapes/general layout will remain the same. The default size is 2048x2048.
